{"author":{"id":"1949ffc23f11a8cb4f8c42a45c9ad241b49570df9a18687489e9ea78d87c54a3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1772048178,"nonce":"Dxa0KXf+ZA3nl4GBi+euBXDQwjE=","title":"State browser panel for advanced loss/probe targeting","message":"[Imported from GitHub #47] (created 2026-01-30T04:18:06Z)\n\n## Summary\n\nAdd a state browser panel as an advanced fallback for targeting loss terms and probes. This is lower priority than the primary probe-based workflow but provides power users with direct access to the full state tree.\n\n## Context\n\nThe primary state selection mechanism is **probe nodes** (visual, graph-first), with a **port context menu** shortcut (\"Add loss term here\" auto-creates and wires a probe). The state browser is an advanced alternative for:\n\n- Targeting internal state not exposed via ports\n- Exploring the full state tree structure\n- Power users who prefer path-based selection\n\n## Requirements\n\n1. **Backend introspection API**: Expose the model's state tree structure to the UI\n   - Return hierarchical state paths (e.g., `mechanics.effector.pos`, `network.hidden`)\n   - Include array shapes and dtypes for display\n\n2. **UI panel**: Collapsible tree view showing state hierarchy\n   - Click to select a path\n   - Selected path can be used as loss target or probe binding\n   - Search/filter by path name\n\n3. **Integration**: Selected paths should work with the existing `WhereDict` string selector pattern\n\n## Notes\n\n- `WhereDict.key_transform` already supports string selectors\n- `attr_str_tree_to_where_func` can reconstruct callables from string paths\n- This requires runtime model introspection, which isn't currently exposed to the UI\n\n---\nCo-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.5 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}